		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53f3682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>4:17.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Search and seizure—Schools</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="134"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>School searches present a variation of the “private person” problem. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1974129392" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic299e08274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Young v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I77eca3a074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] an assistant principal of a public high school directed the defendant, a 17-year-old student, to empty his pockets in the principal&apos;s office. <eos/>
						<bos/>The defendant was charged and convicted for possessing less than an ounce of marijuana. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that the school official was a government officer subject to the restraints of the Fourth Amendment and that the evidence should have been suppressed. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court reversed[<footnote.reference refid="I77eca3a174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] holding that the assistant high school principal was not a “public officer” or “law enforcement officer” and the “reasonable suspicion” standard was sufficient for the search.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77eca3a274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Subsequently, the Court of Appeals followed <ital>Young</ital> in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1976115778" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic29bdc5274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>State v. Lamb</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I77eca3a374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] where it upheld the “reasonable suspicion” standard in a dormitory supervisor&apos;s search of a dormitory room in which marijuana plants were growing.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>However, if a law enforcement officer (even one working an additional job as a security guard) assists school personnel in the search, the search is held to the higher probable cause standard.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77eccab074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1985102641" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Ic29d62f474d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>New Jersey v. T.L.O.</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I77eccab174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] the United States Supreme Court reiterated that the Fourth Amendment applies to searches conducted by public school officials and the legality the search of a student depends on its reasonableness under all the circumstances.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The Georgia Court of Appeals discussed <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="1985102641" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Ic29ec28474d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>T.L.O.</ital>
						</cite.query> in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018130" w-serial-number="2000395500" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic29ec28774d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Patman v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I77eccab274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] where it explained that <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“a student&apos;s interest in privacy must be balanced against <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>‘the substantial interest of teachers and administrators in maintaining discipline in the classroom and on school grounds.’<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I77ecf1c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] Accordingly, the Fourth Amendment permits school officials to search students based upon circumstances which do not rise to the level of probable cause, and <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>
						<?page no="135"?>“[i]n Georgia, school officials may search subject only to the most minimal restraints necessary to insure that students are not whimsically stripped of personal privacy and subjected to petty tyranny.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I77ecf1c174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
